text: hi everyone
Anthony Fantino here Internet's busiest
music nerd time for an album review the
Black Keys El Camino these beasts these
guys are a rock duo that I've been
following ever since this blues rock and
garage rock revival got kind of huge in
the in the early to mid 2000s I reviewed
their album brothers last year but I got
to be completely honest and say I was
not all that excited to hear El Camino
in all the years I've been listening to
the Black Keys especially releases like
like thickfreakness and rubber factory
and an amazing EP that they have
released of nothing but but junior
Kimbrough songs the duo has never really
thrown me a left hook or a surprise and
this is kind of a complaint I had with
the band's last album
I think it's an even bigger complaint
for me with this album I think the Black
Keys are long overdue for a direction
change you know but there is a silver
lining in that cloud and it is that the
Black Keys are a picture of consistency
every time they drop an album it's got
pretty much the sound you would expect
and it always gets the same semi glowing
or glowing reviews there are some
detractors here and there but not so
many that they would be a big deal and
as long as the Black Keys stick to the
style and the ideas and and the sounds
and the songwriting that has worked for
them up until this point who's really
gonna complain not to say there's been
no change whatsoever in this band's
career earlier releases were much
simpler much more skeletal much more raw
and that changed after the band worked
with Danger Mouse on the album attack
and release but to be honest it's it's
maybe my least favorite Keys album and
ever since then I feel like their songs
have just kind of been
getting simpler and more straightforward
I just think the kind of romantic
interplay that you would get between the
guitar and drums on an album like magic
potion has has kind of faded away a bit
in exchange for writing songs that are
popular hooky er more instant and
because of that I feel like Black Keys
new stuff contains less subtleties
secrets on El Camino you basically kind
of get this same flavor of of modernized
but also nostalgic garage and blues rock
the hooks in roughly the same way the
guitars feature an array of different
tones and effects the drums really
forced some nice grooves the lyrical
subjects revolve around girls and
heartbreak and relationships as usual
with a few kind of stragglers varying
from that formula lots of warm bass
lines fuzzy distorted pentatonic guitar
solos a little extra piano and organ and
background vocals here and there
call me death but I feel like the Black
Keys are working with roughly the same
ideas as they were on brothers with a
few spots here and there that kind of
stick out like the first single lonely
boy
which to me feels like a newer take on
the raw sound the Black Keys used to
play with all the time the track little
black submarine starts off as a really
nice acoustic ballad and actually kind
of sounds like a track maybe the White
Stripes could have written on the album
white blood cells sister has one of the
hardest and catchiest grooves that these
guys have have ever produced and Nova
baby is is a is a notably sunnier song
than a lot of the tracks on here but the
rest of the tracks on here for me don't
really feel new I get tired of ideas
when they feel kind of overused I guess
and when those ideas get overused is is
really kind of a personal preference you
know obviously in my opinion of this
record is heavily impacted by just my
musical preferences and how much music
from these guys
I have heard if you're relatively new to
the Black Keys
maybe brothers for example was was your
first introduction to them you're
probably going to enjoy this and if this
is your first Black Keys album try it
out it's really not that bad it's pretty
solid there's not really any pop holes
or anything but that's because the Black
Keys don't really take that many risks
outside of what has already worked for
them in the past in my opinion it's
consistent it's fast it's easy it's kind
of catchy but I know personally I'm not
gonna remember most of these songs come

here lyrically can get a little corny
like hey nah nah she's a moneymaker hey
